I love ya, Neil, but I need to rewrite your rewrite:

Where it began, was in Wuhan
And now we know it’s growing strong
Was in China
Then people got on the airplanes
Who’d a believed it would come along

Hands, washing hands
No reaching out, don’t touch me, don’t touch you

Sweet quarantine
Old eggs never seemed so good
I’ve been reclined
Like all the rest of the neighborhood
But now I

Look at news and it don’t seem the children
Gonna be going back to school
And when we’re bored
I tell more of my stories
The kids always think they’re cool

One, week number one
Weekends here, now we start, week number two

Sweet quarantine
Old eggs never seemed so good
I’ve been reclined
Like all the rest of the neighborhood

snippet.textDisplay:
Brought me to tears~ tho I never was a “fan” bc I was too young, didn’t realize how your voice was woven into the fabric of my childhood. Hearing your voice flooded me with unexpected, soothing and wonderful memories, as if they were attached to the unique tone of your voice. Thank you for being a part of me, tho I didn’t even know you were.
Seeing you looking so well and so happy to inspire and sing for us makes me very happy! God bless ya xx

snippet.textDisplay: Neil, I'm a retired photographer. I was shooting a wedding for an FBI agent, and his bride, Caroline.  The guests included a bunch of the couples friends, including lots of FBI agents.  When it came time for the couples first dance, one of the FBI agents took the microphone and did a wonderful toast to the couple.  Then the band started playing your wonderful hit, Sweet Caroline.  The FBI agent with the microphone sang your song.  He AMAZED EVERYONE of the guests, and especially the bride. She was crying like a baby while dancing her first dance.  She didn't know this had been arranged by the groom.  The FBI agent singing sounded exactly like you.  He NAILED your famous song.  I'll never forget that couple, and that song, and that first dance.  Thanks for the memories!
